<section class="case-overview">
<h2>Overview</h2>
<p>A student from Dural had their nearly-new MacBook Air M2 suffer a cracked screen when something was caught between the screen and keyboard when the lid closed. The Liquid Retina display showed cracks across the lower third with LCD bleeding. Apple quoted $799 for out-of-warranty screen replacement. We sourced a quality replacement display and completed the repair at a competitive price.</p>
</section>

<section class="case-symptoms">
<h2>Initial Symptoms</h2>
<ul>
  <li>Visible crack pattern in lower-left corner of screen</li>
  <li>LCD bleed (dark spots) spreading from crack points</li>
  <li>Touchbar/function row unaffected (no Touch Bar on this model)</li>
  <li>External display via USB-C worked perfectly</li>
  <li>Mac functionally fine—only display damaged</li>
  <li>AppleCare not purchased—standard warranty doesn't cover accidental damage</li>
</ul>
</section>

<section class="case-diagnosis">
<h2>Assessment</h2>

<h3>Understanding MacBook Air M2 Displays</h3>
<p>The MacBook Air M2 (2022) uses a 13.6-inch Liquid Retina display with these specifications:</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Resolution:</strong> 2560 x 1664 pixels</li>
  <li><strong>Technology:</strong> IPS LCD with True Tone</li>
  <li><strong>Brightness:</strong> 500 nits</li>
  <li><strong>P3 wide color:</strong> Yes</li>
  <li><strong>Design:</strong> Thinner bezels with notch for camera</li>
</ul>

<h3>Damage Assessment</h3>
<p>Physical inspection confirmed:</p>
<ul>
  <li>Impact point at lower-left corner</li>
  <li>Crack propagation across approximately 30% of panel</li>
  <li>LCD liquid crystal bleeding from damaged cells</li>
  <li>Outer glass intact (damage internal to LCD layer)</li>
  <li>Display housing undamaged—no dents or warping</li>
  <li>Camera and sensors in notch unaffected</li>
</ul>
</section>

<section class="case-repair">
<h2>Repair Process</h2>

<h3>Display Assembly Replacement</h3>
<p>The MacBook Air M2 display replaces as a complete assembly (glass, LCD, and housing together):</p>
<ol>
  <li>Removed display from base by disconnecting flex cables at hinge</li>
  <li>Transferred webcam and antenna cables to replacement assembly</li>
  <li>Installed new display assembly and reconnected cables</li>
  <li>Calibrated display using Apple's display calibration process</li>
</ol>

<h3>Calibration</h3>
<p>Post-replacement calibration ensures True Tone and colour accuracy match Apple's standards. This involves connecting to calibration software that writes display profile data to the Mac's paired component storage.</p>

<h3>Testing</h3>
<ul>
  <li>Full resolution verified (2560 x 1664)</li>
  <li>True Tone functioning correctly</li>
  <li>Brightness tested across full range (0-500 nits)</li>
  <li>P3 colour gamut confirmed</li>
  <li>No dead pixels or uniformity issues</li>
  <li>Camera and microphones working</li>
</ul>
</section>

